# OzzBooks — Addendum: Native macOS Client & AI-Assisted Ingestion

This addendum extends `CLAUDE.md` with decisions made after the initial
Phase 1 PWA build was underway. Append this to the main `CLAUDE.md` (or
keep alongside it) so Claude Code has this context in future sessions.

## Context: why this addendum exists

The Phase 1 PWA is mostly working, but has hit a recurring, hard-to-pin-down
**playback loop bug** (chapter-end / next-chapter transition getting stuck)
that has survived multiple fix attempts. Separately, there's a standing
frustration with **filename → title/author/series parsing** during
ingestion, which was never fully reliable.

**Explicit instruction: do not attempt to fix the playback loop bug as
part of this addendum's work.** The items below are additive
investigation/features, not a bugfix task.

## Decision 1: Native macOS client — additive, not a replacement

### What prompted this
Considered whether a native macOS "server app" (replacing the Node
file-serving API) would help the iOS PWA's clunkiness/looping. Conclusion:
**it would not** — the loop bug lives in client-side playback code (likely
service worker / `<audio>` element / chapter-transition state logic), which
runs identically regardless of backend implementation. Swapping the server
doesn't touch that code path, and iOS remains PWA-only regardless (that
constraint hasn't changed — see main `CLAUDE.md` platform constraints
section).

### What a native macOS client *does* offer
A separate, real diagnostic value: a SwiftUI macOS app using `AVPlayer` /
`AVQueuePlayer` for playback sidesteps the entire category of
PWA/WebKit-specific quirks (service worker lifecycle, Cache API eviction,
Media Session API inconsistencies) because none of that infrastructure
exists in a native app. If the same chapter-transition logic behaves
correctly in the native client, that's a strong signal the PWA's loop bug
is environment-specific rather than a flaw in the underlying playback
state design — useful even without fixing the PWA directly.

### Scope — explicitly additive
- **No changes to the existing Node.js sync API or file-serving API.**
  Both stay exactly as they are.
- New: a SwiftUI macOS app (separate repo or subfolder — Claude Code's
  call on the cleanest structure) that consumes the **same existing REST
  endpoints** the PWA already uses: library data, streaming URLs,
  position sync.
- Position sync already stores `{user_id, book_id, position}` generically
  — the native client requires **zero backend/schema changes** to
  participate in the same sync model as the PWA.
- Playback engine: `AVQueuePlayer` (native chaptering/queueing, native
  background audio, no Media Session API translation layer needed).
- Treat this as a parallel client for comparison/diagnostic purposes and
  a nicer Mac-native experience — not a replacement for the PWA, and not
  a dependency for iOS work.

### Distribution note (for later, not urgent)
Native macOS apps distributed outside the App Store don't go through App
Store review — only Gatekeeper/notarization, which requires an Apple
Developer Program membership ($99/year) if you want to avoid
"unidentified developer" warnings when running it on another Mac (e.g.
MacBook Air). Since current use is your own machines, right-click → Open
once (bypassing Gatekeeper) is sufficient for now; no need to enroll in
the paid program unless/until distributing beyond your own devices.

## Decision 2: AI-assisted ingestion — filename/metadata parsing

### Problem being addressed
Filename-based parsing (regex/heuristics) for extracting title, author,
series, and series number from real-world audiobook file/folder naming is
unreliable — naming conventions in the wild are too inconsistent for
pattern matching to generalize well. This has been an ongoing pain point
independent of the playback bug.

### Approach: local-first LLM extraction, with validation and fallback

**Step 1 — Local LLM extraction (primary path).**
Use the existing local LM Studio setup on the Mac mini (same pattern as
prior Gemma experimentation) to run a structured-extraction pass over
filenames, folder structure, and any embedded ID3/M4B metadata. Candidate
models: Gemma 3 12B, Qwen 2.5 14B, or Llama 3.1 8B, quantized (Q4/Q5) —
comfortable fit for the M4 Pro's 24GB unified memory. This is a batch,
infrequent task (runs during ingestion/rescan, not per-playback), so
inference speed is not a hard constraint.

**Step 2 — Metadata lookup/enrichment (validation).**
Take the local model's rough guess (title/author/series) and query an
external books metadata source (Google Books API, Open Library, or
similar) to confirm or correct it against real book data, and to pull an
authoritative cover image / series number if the local guess was
incomplete. This catches cases where the local model's inference was
close but not quite right.

**Step 3 — Cloud LLM fallback (edge cases only).**
For extractions that remain low-confidence after steps 1–2 (e.g. no
metadata match found, or the local model flags low confidence), fall back
to a cloud API call (e.g. Claude API) for a stronger inference pass. This
should be the exception path, not the default — most of the library
should resolve via steps 1–2 alone, keeping cost near zero and everything
local by default.

### Where this lives
This is entirely an **ingestion-pipeline concern**, independent of native
vs. PWA client work. It runs in the existing Node ingestion service (or
wherever ingestion currently lives) and benefits every client
automatically, since ingestion output is shared.

## Decision 3: AI-assisted filename/folder cleanup on disk

### What this adds beyond Decision 2
Decision 2 produces a *clean normalized model* used internally by the app
(title/author/series shown in the UI) without touching the actual files.
This decision is about optionally **renaming/reorganizing the real files
on the NAS** to match a consistent convention (e.g.
`{Series} {Number} - {Title}/{ChapterNum} - {ChapterTitle}.{ext}`), using
the same extraction pipeline's output as the source of truth for new
names.

### Required safeguards — non-negotiable given this touches real files
- **Opt-in only, per book.** Never renames automatically as part of
  routine ingestion. Ingestion produces *proposals*; nothing is written
  to the NAS without explicit user action.
- **Preview before write.** Every rename batch must show a full diff (old
  path → proposed new path) for review/edit before anything is applied.
- **Undo log.** Maintain a persistent record (simple table or JSON log)
  of original → renamed path mappings per batch, so any rename operation
  can be reversed. This is the kind of feature where a silent bad batch
  rename is a genuinely bad failure mode — treat reversibility as a hard
  requirement, not a nice-to-have.

### Suggested data model addition
```
rename_operations
  id, batch_id, book_id,
  original_path, new_path,
  applied_at, reverted_at (nullable)
```

## Summary of what to build (for Claude Code)

1. **Native macOS client** (new, additive) — SwiftUI + `AVQueuePlayer`,
   consumes existing REST API and position-sync model unchanged. No
   backend changes required. Purpose: nicer native experience on Mac +
   diagnostic comparison against the PWA's playback bug (without fixing
   that bug directly).
2. **Local-first AI ingestion parsing** (ingestion pipeline change) —
   LM Studio local model → metadata lookup validation → cloud fallback
   for low-confidence cases only.
3. **Optional filesystem cleanup feature** (new, opt-in) — proposes
   renamed/reorganized files on the NAS using ingestion's extraction
   output, gated behind preview + explicit approval + undo log.

None of the above should touch or attempt to resolve the existing PWA
playback loop bug — that remains a separate, already-in-progress issue
outside the scope of this addendum.
